M a n B i r d â„¢ 2023-02-04 12:53 AM
My tip I guess for that would be experiment with layering, feeling like some chords sound thin? Add an extra layer of another sound. Liking the snare but it's lacking punch? Find another sound and blend them. I often do this with supersaws and stuff where it might be 4 or 5 different layers from sometimes different synths with slightly different effects or each playing part of the full chord, just try some stuff and combine things
12:54 AM
Also ear candy, feeling like there's a big empty space after a phrase? Add a subtle counter melody, or put in a subtle arp or something
12:58 AM
The layering also applies to vocals, if you feel those are thin or could use some more. I often layer in another take sung an octave higher, and / or duplicate the main vocal and shift that an octave higher, also just the main melody at a lower volume slightly panned to each side or with other compression settings. You can build stuff as full as you like. Ted talk over lol, lots of stuff to say I guess haha, happy to help tho if you feel like it's useful

Maybe this change was part of your remix, but the lead melody has a different rhythm than the original, and I think that contributes to it sounding jarring. I think it would also sound better if the chords have a simpler rhythm, maybe one that aligns with the melody. If it is hard to change the entire melody on the phone, I'd suggest putting just one bar on loop and experimenting with rhythm on that, once you find something that works, you can extend that rhythm for the entire melody / chord progression.
